StringWithMarkup.String: Chlorothalonil appears as colorless crystals or granules or light gray powder. Melting point 250-251°C. No odor when pure; technical grade has a slightly pungent odor. A fungicide formulated as water-dispersible granules, wettable powder, or dust.

Tendency of a material to resist change or decomposition due to internal reaction, or due to the action of air, heat, light, pressure, etc. (See also Stability and Reactivity section under Safety and Hazards)

StringWithMarkup.String: Thermally stable at ambient temperatures. Stable to u.v. light in aqueous media and in crystalline state. Stable in acidic and moderately alkaline aqueous solutions; slow hydrolysis at pH >9.

Reference: Tomlin CDS, ed. Chlorothalonil (1897-45-6). In: The e-Pesticide Manual, 13th Edition  Version 3.2 (2005-06). Surrey UK, British Crop Protection Council.

StringWithMarkup.String: It breaks down at pH 9, the rate following first-order kinetics at 1.8% per day (at 25 °C). It has been shown that chlorothalonil is unstable to light when dissolved in benzene and that 2,3,5-trichloro-4,6-dicyanobiphenyl is a condensation product.

Reference: WHO; Environ Health Criteria 183: Chlorothalonil p.34 (1996). Available from, as of January 27, 2006: http://www.inchem.org/documents/ehc/ehc/ehc183.htm
